
ITEMSHAPE (ZOOM) – WORKING NOTE

Purpose:
Sound-shaping zone for selected items.
Not for physical item placement/nudging.

CORE LAWS
- Faders and rotaries mirror the same channel parameter.
- Fader = continuous/macro control.
- Rotary = stepped/discrete control.
- Option = fine / alternate control in this zone.
- Shift + Jog = add more items to selection while staying in this zone.
- Rotaries handle list stepping/cycling.
- Select buttons are NOT for long list cycling here.
- Select buttons MAY be used for fixed anchor values where useful.
- Flip = phase invert (for now).

BUTTON LOGIC
- Record Arm row = lock/availability per channel.
- Red ON = available / active for editing.
- Dark = locked / unavailable.
- Mute row = bypass or audition the relevant channel effect.
- We already have lock, so Mute is for listen / bypass behaviour.

CHANNEL LAYOUT

CH 1 – PITCH
- Fader 1 = pitch coarse
- Rotary 1 = semitone steps
- Option + Fader 1 = fine pitch
- Option + Rotary 1 = fine stepped pitch
- Select 1 = fixed musical anchors:
  0 -> +7 -> +12 -> -12 -> back round
  (normal / 5th / octave up / octave down)

CH 2 – PLAYRATE / TIME
- Fader 2 = playrate coarse
- Rotary 2 = stepped playrate
- Option + Fader 2 = fine playrate
- Option + Rotary 2 = fine stepped playrate
- Select 2 use not fixed yet

CH 3 – PAN
- Fader 3 = pan coarse
- Rotary 3 = stepped pan
- Option + Fader 3 = fine pan
- Option + Rotary 3 = fine stepped pan
- Select 3 use not fixed yet

CH 4 – CROSSFADE CENTER
- Fader 4 = crossfade center / splice position coarse
- Rotary 4 = stepped crossfade center movement
- Option + Fader 4 = fine center movement
- Option + Rotary 4 = fine stepped center movement
- Select 4 = cycle crossfade shape
- Record Arm 4 = lock availability
- Mute 4 = audition / focus listen on the crossfade intersection

CH 5 – CROSSFADE LENGTH
- Fader 5 = crossfade length coarse
- Rotary 5 = stepped crossfade length
- Option + Fader 5 = fine crossfade length
- Option + Rotary 5 = fine stepped crossfade length
- Select 5 = fixed default crossfade length anchor
- Record Arm 5 = lock availability
- Mute 5 = bypass crossfade / hear the hard cut

CH 6 – FADE IN
- Fader 6 = fade in length
- Rotary 6 = fade in shape / stepped fade options
- Record Arm 6 = lock availability
- Mute 6 = bypass fade-in effect

CH 7 – FADE OUT
- Fader 7 = fade out length
- Rotary 7 = fade out shape / stepped fade options
- Record Arm 7 = lock availability
- Mute 7 = bypass fade-out effect

CH 8 – ITEM VOLUME
- Fader 8 = item volume coarse
- Rotary 8 = stepped volume
- Option + Fader 8 = fine volume
- Option + Rotary 8 = fine stepped volume
- Select 8 could be fixed anchors like -6 / 0 / +6 if wanted later
- Mute 8 = mute item

WHY 4 AND 5 NOW MAKE SENSE
- Crossfades are a big part of item shaping.
- They belong here because they affect the transition between items, not physical item placement.
- Channel 4 controls where the transition sits.
- Channel 5 controls how wide the transition is.
- This makes the middle of the surface the transition cluster.
- Left side stays tone / time / space.
- Right side stays amplitude envelope.

AUDITION / BYPASS LOGIC FOR CROSSFADES
- Mute 4 = listen focus on the overlap / transition area.
- Mute 5 = bypass the crossfade so the raw edit can be heard.
- Record Arm 4 and 5 = on/off availability for editing those crossfade controls.

NOTES
- Fade in on 6, fade out on 7, item volume on 8 feels right together.
- Right hand = amplitude envelope cluster.
- Left side = tone / time / space.
- Middle = transition / crossfade handling.
- Crossfade control on 4 and 5 is more useful than leaving them empty if crossfades are a repeated action.
- Keep this zone uncluttered.
- Only add functions that solve real repeated actions.

CURRENT OPEN QUESTIONS
